<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-641-128  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 641 128.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  July 16 1990 n377 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Resellers, analysts question results of Microsoft study of GUIproductivity. (Windows 3.0 under the microscope) (graphical userinterface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shore, Joel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp reports a 58 percent productivity improvement in acomparative study of graphical- versus command-driven userinterfaces.andP;  The user study involving 120 experienced and noviceusers compares Microsoft Windows 3.0 and MS-DOS running variousword processing and spreadsheet software applications.andP;  The reportindicates that GUI users perform more work and perform it moreaccurately than those using a character-based interface.andO;Microsoft claims that GUI users performed 35 percent more tasks inthe same amount of time.andP;  They also have a better accuracy score,completing 91 percent of the tasks correctly compared to 74percent for command-driven interface users.andP;  The major criticismof the study is that it was conducted in a controlled settinginstead of a typical usage environment, such as an actualbusiness.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (reports).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (surveys).andO;Topic:     User SurveyGraphical User InterfaceCommand-Driven User InterfacesComparative Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>